data.title: Coffee is terrible and food prices high
data.text: This is now called "Rustica".  While it's a cool historic building, none of us like the coffee and we checked out the breakfast menu last week and prices are too high for the product.  The egg sandwich is too expensive and the size is comparable to any of the other egg sandwiches at fast food places. While it's a cool building and we've been there many times for tea, it's difficult to have a combersation because the rooms echo if there are lots of people there.  Sometimes it's difficult to find seating because there are lots of singles there occupying a table alone with their laptops and a cup of coffee.  I hope the business is successful under their new branding as it's nice for our area.

data.title: this is one of the coolest buildings i've been in
data.text: it feels like a cool old house. they did a great job setting it all up. i mean the coffee and everything is good of course but it's really all about that place. takes your mind rambling places when you're there.

data.title: Wonderful for small meetings
data.text: Best coffee in the Twin Cities!  Atmosphere is laid back, not too busy, comfortable to meeting with friends or small groups.  The Hosta Garden in the park next door is a hidden gem!

data.title: Beautiful place - worst service I've had in ages
data.text: This place is absolutely beautiful - old house, gazebo and vine-covered patio, several rooms inside with lots of tables. Free WiFi. That said, this past Sunday afternoon, I (and a few others) waited way too long for our drinks. It took 25 minutes to get my chai. They hadn't forgotten my order; it just took that long. Had I not been waiting to meet someone, I would have left. The baristas were working slowly, didn't let me know they were understaffed or there would be a delay, and in the end, offered not even the slightest apology. No "sorry for the wait" - nothing. Five stars for the environment, three for the chai, zero for the service.

data.title: Ahhhhh!  Respite!!!
data.text: Lovely site, lots of nooks and crannies to meet and talk, or not.  Good coffee, and a real turntable playing real records in a historic, nicely preserved house as well as easy to find due to its primo location on well known roads.

data.title: Perhaps the most unique coffee shop in Twin Cities - beautiful
data.text: This place is in a historic farmhouse.  It's beautiful.  There are many rooms and free wi-fi. Also some lovely stained glass windows.  The food is good and drinks are like other Dunn Brothers.  But this is a truly unique place.  They make it available for community meetings.

data.title: Lukewarm Coffee and Barista's with no personality!
data.text: I usually love this Dunn Brother's but yesterday when I went in to get my birthday coffee I had the worst experience ever!  My coffee was not hot and neither was my husband's and unfortunately we got our coffee to go and didn't try it before leaving the building!  My salted caramel latte was pretty tasteless as in couldn't taste any salt or any caramel and the baristas added nothing to the experience.  I like a barista that actually talks to you and the two working on January 10th were a couple of duds!

data.title: Delightful place for a good cup of coffee!
data.text: I love the Dunn Brothers in Eden Prairie, their historic setting is so unique and they have done a great job of maintaining the house and the grounds are beautiful as well.  The only sad part is they lost the huge tree that used to shade the patio and they don't have any umbrellas out there.  It is such a beautiful place to sit but they need to invest in some umbrellas as there are only a few tables in the shade and on a hot day, it is not comfortable sitting out there in the sun! I also love the old turntable they play records on, takes me back to my youth! Coffee and food is very good and service is excellent, so what more could you ask for, oh yeah, umbrellas!

data.title: Historic house/coffee shop
data.text: Best coffee shop in Eden Prairie.  Historic Smith Douglas More House is a great setting for a multi-roomed, multi-floored coffee house with seasonal patio seating.  Drink fresh-roasted coffee, tea, soft drinks, wine, beer; eat a bakery item or sandwich; relax and enjoy LP albums from back in the day.  WiFi, discounted coffee in washable cups, friendly baristas, and sometime music add to the value.

data.title: Interesting locaiton, nice surprises
data.text: Great service at this Dunn Bro's location.  Not only are the grounds and building interesting, but the service is good, and the food menu is unique.  My only negative, some of the crotchety patrons who believe it is their private club house...  Can't blame the proprietors for that though.

data.title: A charming spot with a great atmosphere!
data.text: Dunn Bros. Coffee in Eden Prairie is darling!  It's located in an historic farmhouse, built in 1877 and originally used as a stop-over for train travelers.  Now the nearby train tracks are gone, and in their place is a well-maintained biking/walking trail that goes for miles across the Twin Cities.  I love stopping here for iced coffee during a bike ride, or for hot coffee or breakfast during mid-winter visits to Minneapolis.
